The Shack
v1.8 | Copyright 2020 - 2021

by System Masters

Story, writing and game design: Mat Cooper
Artwork: Mark Ferrari  (www.markferrari.com). Additional artwork used under CCL from freely available sources. Audio: Freesound.org used under CCL
PRESS ANY KEY TO CONTINUE

The Shack is a classic text adventure, where you interact with the game world by typing in what you wish to do, followed by pressing enter to see the outcome of your actions. The parser will attempt to understand complex sentences and run-on commands, as well as identifying last used items. This means you can try things such as "take the key and examine it, then use the key to unlock the door". The easiest way to play however, is using the classic Verb/Noun combination. For example "get key" "exam key" "use key on door". On a container however, you could just try "unlock [container name]" whilst carrying the key. Below are a list of example commands, but not all of them... I don't want to give any of the game away, after all!

Look, L    will repeat the room description for you
Examine, Exam, Ex, X, look at    will describe an object or something you can see in the game world
Take, Get    will attempt to pick up an item
Inventory, Inv, I    will show what you are carrying around
N, S, E, W, NW, NE, SW, SE, In, Out, Up, Down   will move you in that direction
Use [ITEM] on [THING]   will do just that

You can also try specific things, such as hit, cut, swim, climb, pull, push   and many more.

I've tried to make the game as user friendly as possible, whilst not easing up on the puzzles. There are subtle hints buried in item descriptions and other places though, so be sure to look at everything you can!

Don't forget to save   your game too, if you get stuck and wish to come back later.

Good luck, and have fun!

PRESS ANY KEY TO CONTINUE

You open your eyes.

Darkness.

You blink rapidly, trying to focus on anything around you. As your eyes become accustomed to the gloom, you make out a vague sliver of light coming through a thin crack in the room's western wall. You have no idea where you are, but at least you know you're not blind.

It's then you notice the cold, and realise the disturbing truth: You're naked. You have no idea why, and no clue as to where you are or how you ended up here.

A million thoughts run through your mind, but you focus on what little you can ascertain: You're not injured, or at least you don't feel it. You're able bodied, although your mind feels slightly fuzzy, as if you should know how you ended up here or even what you were doing last, but you can't recall either of those things. You're not even sure where you should be.

OK, it's time to pull yourself together. You need to find a light source, scope out where you are, find some clothes and whatever else seems useful and get the hell out of here. Discovering what exactly happened to you can wait until you've gotten at least as far as that.

You can see a sliver of light coming from a crack in the wall ahead of you. The rest of the room is in total darkness.

> x crack

> x crack
The light filters through ever so slightly, illuminating a cord hanging in front of it.
> pull cord

> pull cord
Dislodging several layers of dust, you tentatively pull on the cord. Much to your relief, it is a light switch - it even works! The whole of the shack is bathed in a nicotine glow from a bare bulb above your head.
Press any key to continue
You're in a small, wooden shack; little more than a garden shed. The floor and walls are thick with decades of dust, the air heavy and stifled.
A curtain hangs ceiling to floor behind you, moth-eaten and sagging from rings which have rusted over time. One long shelf manages to maintain its holding against the shacks eastern wall, whilst a metal trunk lies beneath it, a stalwart sentinel refusing to give in to countless years of neglect.
There are no signs of life inside the shack except for you.
There's one way out: A door right in front of you.
Now you can see what you're doing, on to the second order of business: finding some clothes and getting out of here.
You can see a cord and a curtain.

> x shelf

> x shelf
like everything else in here, is covered with a thick layer of dust.
On it sits a Toolbox.
> open toolbox

> open toolbox
You prise the latch from it's rusted moorings, and flip the lid on the toolbox.
> take screwdriver

> take screwdriver
You pick it up.
> take nails

> take nails
You carefully pick up the nails, trying not to stab yourself as you do so.
> pull curtain

> pull curtain
You pull back the curtain, avoiding the thick dust; two moths skim your face and head straight for the yellowing light bulb hanging above your head.
> x flower pots

> x flower pots
You lift the stack of plant pots, and look through them.
Inside one of the pots is a small key.
> take small key

> take small key
You pick it up.
> unlock trunk

> unlock trunk
Using the small key you found in the flower pots, you unlock the trunk.
> open trunk

> open trunk
You grab the handles on either side of the trunk's lid and heave it upwards. It thuds against the wall of the shack, causing a sprinkling of dry rot to coat the shelf above.
The trunk houses a set of farmhand clothes.
> take clothes

> take clothes
You pick up the full set of clothes
> wear clothes

> wear clothes
The clothes are a little too small, but it doesn't matter - you're no longer naked, and you're ready to leave the shack!
> out

> out
Your eyes burn against the light of the great outdoors, and it takes a moment for your vision to adjust. How long had you been holed up in there?  Why  were you in there? If you were kidnapped, surely you'd have been left in a more secure location. Hell, you probably wouldn't have been left alone in there, that's for damn sure. And the door wasn't even locked...

But in there you were. Alone. Naked. Confused.

But now you're out. It's time to look around, figure out where you are and find out exactly what happened to you - one step at a time.

You're outside the old, dilapidated shack, lush green grass clawing at its walls as Mother Nature threatens to reclaim it. The path you're standing on stretches away from the door of your former temporary prison before splitting off in several directions. The spot is marked by a large rock. To the West, you can see woodland in the distance, whilst directly behind you the path continues on through green fields. To the East, it drops off out of view.

Some distance away you can see a small village. You have no intention of going that far unless absolutely necessary, as a huge lake shimmers before it, presenting a barrier that would be at least a day's walk to bypass.

With nothing to go on and no clue of where you are, all you can do is explore and hope to find some answers. You try to stay as rational as possible, and focus on what to do next.
There are paths going in, south, west or east.

> w

> w
You are following an east to west footpath in the countryside. To the east, you can see the roof of the shack. Some way off to the west, the path disappears into dense woodland.
You can go east or west.

> w

> w
You're at the western edge of a country trail, where it disappears into thick woodland. The sun's rays are scattered by the encroaching canopy of the trees to the west, and what remains of a wooden fence marks a boundary long since forgotten. To the east, the path continues, eventually leading back to the shack.
You can go east or west.

> x fence

> x fence
What remains of the wooden fence runs along the northerm edge of the path, presumably once built to keep livestock from wandering into the woods.
 The end post is still standing upright... and has something carved into it. You squat beside it for a moment to read the message roughly hewn into the wood: "Leave. Think!". Certainly not your average graffiti.
 Below the fence post, lying in the grass, is a folded pocket knife.
> take pocket knife

> take pocket knife
You pick it up.
> w

> w
You are deep in thick woodland, at the western end of a trail. It peters out from here, although you can follow it back to the east which will take you to the entrance of the woods. A small, algae coated pond fills an earthen pit in the ground behind you, a gnarled crab apple tree standing at its edge, reaching skyward to grasp what sunlight filters through.
You can go east or north.

> x tree

> x tree
The tree appears to be thriving here, long roots growing into the murky water around its base and shafts of light from above sustaining its growth. Several crab apples lie rotting on the floor around it, and more float atop the green algae which feeds off the pond. There are still a number of ripe ones hanging from the tree's branches though. The base of the trunk features a large hollow.
> take crab apple

> take crab apple
You pick up the small apple and pop it into your pocket.
> n

> n
You amble north along what little route through the undergrowth there is, until you are stopped in your tracks by a wall of overgrown reeds and pampas grass. You hear the sound of running water beyond, and push through the thick plants to burst out on the other side.

You find yourself standing on the edge of a sparkling stream, its crystalline water lapping at the grassy banks as it meanders around pebbles and stones. The air here is clear and refreshing, the trees not as thick as deeper within the woods. The sound of running water momentarily gives you the urge to urinate, but it soon passes. You feel completely at peace. The path south leads deeper into the woods, whilst to the north the trees appear to thin out even further.
You can go south or north.

> drink stream

> drink stream
You lay prone by the edge of the stream, your face suspended over the surface. With cupped hands, you take several large gulps of the crisp, refreshing water. It's immediately satisfying, and you remain there for a few moments, just looking across the surface.

It's then that you notice what's laying in the grass next to you - you'd have missed it if you weren't laying right by it. It's a tiny brass key, the kind that may fit a small jewellery box, or perhaps a simple padlock.
> take brass key

> take brass key
You collect the key from between the blades of the dewey grass.
