> s
You're walking along a rough footpath which meanders north to south through the countryside. To the north is the shack, and to the south the footpath begins to wind its way through farmland.
You can go north or south.

> s

> s
You are walking through the middle of a field, at a point where worn footpaths intersect in a crossroads fashion. The wisps of cloud drifting in the sky contrast against the lush green sea of grass which surrounds you; you feel peaceful in this idyllic place. For a moment you almost forget you don't know where you are or how you got here. You cannot let the beauty of the place distract you!

A small circle of standing stones surround an overgrown patch in the field, clearly a manmade monument of sorts. Upright stones hold slabs above them in a way reminiscent of Stonehenge, but far less grand in scale.
You can go south, east, north or west.

> x stones

> x stones
Although not as magnificent as its inspiration, the stones are still a sight to behold. Eight upright columns of rock stretch around twelve feet into the air, with some pairs holding aloft a horizontal slab between them, like a series of doorways.
> x slabs

> x slabs
The slabs stretch across the upright stones like doorway mantles.
You notice something atop one of them: a bundle of twigs and earth, which appears to be moving! A whistling noise pierces the air making you jump as a bird emerges from the nest, swoops down to the ground, then flies back up again. You're pretty sure it's a magpie.
> x magpie

> x magpie
You watch as the magpie swoops down to the ground, pokes its beak into the soft earth a few times, then flies back up to its nest atop the stone circle. It seems to be looking for food.
> use crab apple on magpie

> use crab apple on magpie
The next time the magpie flies down, you gently roll the crab apple you found in the woods towards it.  For a moment the bird is startled, but you remain crouched and still a few feet away. The magpie takes a few tentative hops towards the small fruit before testing it with its beak. It seems to enjoy it, as it hammers away until the small apple breaks into two, and flies off to its nest with a piece of it in its beak!

As the magpie drops the crab apple into its nest, it dislodges a metallic disk it had squirrelled away in there - a coin of some sort. The coin bounces off the stone with a bright ting, and lands in the dirt at the side of you.
> take coin

> take coin
You pick up the coin and place it into your shirt pocket.
> e

> e
You are trudging through the middle of a wheat field, thickly grown and ready to reap. Roughly in the centre of the field stands something you don't recall ever seeing in real life: A scarecrow, strung up like a lifeless corpse, crucified in the name of keeping the wildlife away from the crops.
You can go west.

> x scarecrow

> x scarecrow
The scarecrow is tied to a wooden stake in the middle of the field, arms held out in a classic T pose. It appears to be largely made of straw, and is decorated with a waxed weatherproof jacket, leather gloves and an old, wide-brimmed hat.
> x jacket

> x jacket
The jacket, although of no use to you as a garment, is largely intact. It has two deep pockets at the hem, and opens at the front.
> open jacket

> open jacket
You reach out to the front of the jacket, and fold back the opening. The jacket has a small inside pocket, out of which appears to stick a crumpled up piece of note paper.
> take crumpled note

> take crumpled note
You pick it up.
> x pockets

> x pockets
You rummage through the pockets in turn, despite being unsure of the urge which compels you to do so.
Inside the left hand pocket, your fingers wrap around something small and cylindrical, which feels cold and metallic to the touch. You pull your hand free - it's a battery. A standard, AA cell, looking a little worse for wear. You taket the battery, trying not to think too hard about why it would be in the pocket of a scarecrow.
> w

> w
You are walking through the middle of a field, at a point where worn footpaths intersect in a crossroads fashion. The wisps of cloud drifting in the sky contrast against the lush green sea of grass which surrounds you; you feel peaceful in this idyllic place.

A small circle of standing stones surround an overgrown patch in the field, clearly a manmade monument of sorts. Upright stones hold slabs above them in a way reminiscent of Stonehenge, but far less grand in scale.
