> w

> w
You're standing by a fallen dry stone wall, once designed to keep trespassers out of what was probably a working farm. Several crumbling buildings are dotted across the landscape, their doors long since rotted away and their windows home to staccato shards of mouldy glass. A worn path, little more than a trail of dirt, snakes across to a stable over the way. The long grass grabs at your ankles as you move off the path to look around the area, and you almost trip over an ancient, round millstone buried within the green velt.

To the northwest, the trail splits off, heading to a silo beyond - apart from the stable to the west, it's the only other building here you'd feel safe exploring.
You can go east, west or northwest.

> w

> w
Inside, the stables are still fairly intact. There are half a dozen stocks for keeping animals separated, with bits of straw still lining most of them despite the asbsence of any actual livestock. A wrought iron bracket for holding farm tools is fastened across the length of one wall.

There are two doorways in and out of this place: To the east you can see the ruined farm buildings you passed earlier, and a much larger exit leads out, way off to the west, where the path stops at a small farm house in the distance.
You can go east or west.

> x bracket

> x bracket
The bracket is designed to hold an array of farming and gardening tools.
It holds one tool: a long handled cultivator.
The bracket is securely fastened, with hinges at one end and two screws at the other preventing you from opening it.
> use screwdriver on screws

> use screwdriver on screws
You place the tip of the screwdriver against the frist screw... It's a perfect fit. You remember the old adage "lefty loosey, righty tighty" and quickly remove both screws from the bracket, letting it swing open.
> take cultivator

> take cultivator
You lift the cultivator from its housing, and take it with you.
> take screws

> take screws
You're not sure why, but you decide to take the screws with you.
> w

> w
You're standing at the front gate of a large farm house. Contrary to the rest of the surroundings, it appears well maintained: The front garden is bursting with colour from several flower beds, window boxes are full of delicate plants, and ornately patterned wooden beams surround the front door of the house.

Maybe you'll find answers here, answers to where you are and how you got here. Or maybe you'll find the people who took your clothes and left you in that shack... Probably best to proceed with caution, you think.
You can see a house.
You can go east.

> knock on farm door

> knock on farm door
You take a deep breath, and knock hard on the wooden door with the back of your hand. You don't hear anything. you glance at the windows, looking for signs of movement from within. Again, nothing. It looks like the place is empty... You open the door, allowing you access.
> in

> in
With a deep breath, you open the door and set foot inside the house. You stop for a moment before closing the door behind you, checking one final time that nobody is home. You're inside the farm house, standing in an east to west hallway. The place feels cosy and comfortable; very rustic. The heavy wood floor has a slim, red carpet running along its centre, and you feel the comfort of your feet sinking into  it's deep pile. To the east and west, the hallway ends in opaque wooden doors, whilst in front of you a narrow staircase leads upwards. Opposite the front door is a bureau, the wall behind it supporting a number of framed paintings depicting serene country and seaside vistas.
You can go out, up, east or west.

> e

> e
You've wandered into a gloriously old-fashioned kitchen. Terracotta tiles pave the floor, and oak work surfaces surround the walls. Beneath the window which looks out over the garden is a deep, ceramic sink complete with brass taps, polished to a fine sheen. A huge stove sits against the western wall, its many hobs an irresistible invite to any budding cook. Across the top of the room, copper pans of all different shapes and sizes hang by their handles. The place is extremely well kept, but appears sadly under used.
You can go west, east or south.

> x sink

> x sink
The sink is brilliantly clean. It's made of smooth, white ceramic and deeply set into the counter, in an old-fashioned farm house sort of way. On the top of the sink is a rubber plug, sitting by a small length of chain. It looks like someone was about to install it, then left it here.
> take small chain

> take small chain
you wrap the small chain up and put it in your pocket.
> e

> e
You find yourself standing inside a small, cold pantry. A stone table runs along one wall, designed to keep meats cold, although nothing rests on it at the moment. In fact, the shelves which run around the pantry are empty as well - there's no food in sight anywhere.
You can go west.

> x shelves

> x shelves
You stand on your tiptoes to see to the back of the uppermost shelf. Aha! There is something up here after all - a meat tenderising mallet.
> take mallet

> take mallet
You take the mallet with you.
