This appears to be the farmhouse utility room.  An open top washing basket lies by the doorway, with a makeshift clothes line hanging above it, populated by grimy plastic pegs. On the wall opposite the basket, a washing machine and a tumble dryer stand side by side in perpertual servitude, ready to clean and dry whenever needed.
You can go east or south.

> x tumble dryer

> x tumble dryer
The dryer is big, old and rusty. A long pipe connects to a purpose built extractor in the wall behind it.
> x extractor

> x extractor
As you move around the side of the dryer to examine the extractor and the pipe leading to it, you notice something laying behind it: A can of lubricating oil. You guess it slipped down the back of the tumble dryer due to the vibtrations when running it.
> take oil

> take oil
You pick it up.
> use oil on pocket knife

> use oil on pocket knife
You take out the oil can and spray it along the hinge of the pocket knife. With a little wiggling, you manage to free the blade from the handle! The knife now works as intended, but you're disappointed to see the blade is dull and blunt.
The can of oil has sputtered it's last, however - it's final job completed, you discard it.
> s

> s
You find yourself in the living room of the farm house. A thick sheepskin rug dominates the floor space here, a tempting resting spot in front of a stone fireplace. A long bookcase runs the full length of one wall, crammed with tomes of all shapes and sizes. A rustic looking corduroy sofa curves around the edge of the rug just in front of the bookcase, facing the fireplace. Underneath the window at the back of the room is a large, comfortable looking chair, big enough to tuck your legs up into. You imagine sitting there, reading a book in front of a roaring fire. If you were going to build a place for you to live in for the rest of your life, this would be exactly what you'd choose. You've never been here before, but it feels inviting. It feels like home.
You can go north.

> x fireplace

> x fireplace
The fireplace stands still, a hearth of cold stone with no trace of ash in the grate. You can't even see anything to make a fire with - no scuttle, no poker, nothing. It's only then you notice the surround - a simple oak mantlepiece running across the chimney breast.
> x mantlepiece

> x mantlepiece
The mantle is bare save for a single framed photograph standing at one end.
> take photograph

> take photograph
You lift the photograph from the mantlepiece. It's surpsingly heavy! The frame is only a light wood... Curious, you flip the photo over. On the back, secured to the frame with tape, is a heavy looking key. Why it's hidden here is anyone's guess. You replace the photo where you found it, on the end of the mantlepiece.
> take heavy key

> take heavy key
You prise the heavy key from behind the photograph, and stuff it in your pocket.
