The cave mouth forms a tunnel as it runs into the rock, sloping slightly downhill as you follow it. You continue on a way until the light from your torch stops reflecting off the rocks around you - you've reached a larger space beneath the earth. You shine your torch around the space you're in and take in your surroundings.
You're in a large undeground chamber, standing by the tunnel which leads back to the mouth of the cave. It must have taken months, if not years, to hollow this space out - every surface is solid stone, and occasional striations along them give the impression of people grinding away at the walls, floor and ceiling with tools. Indeed, by the light of your torch, you can make out the discoloured patterns of ores and perhaps gems within the rock itself.

Opposite where you entered by is a wooden trough, perhaps which once held water, or maybe the ores and gems of the miners who've worked here. There's even the remains of a geode, an open shell by the trough, surrounded by old, broken and rusted tools.
You can see a pick axe.
You can go northwest or out.

> take pick axe

> take pick axe
As large and heavy as it is, you decide to take the pick axe with you.
