You are deep in thick woodland, at the western end of a trail. It peters out from here, although you can follow it back to the east which will take you to the entrance of the woods. A small, algae coated pond fills an earthen pit in the ground behind you, a gnarled crab apple tree standing at its edge, reaching skyward to grasp what sunlight filters through.
You can go east or north.

> x pond

> x pond
Thick with algae, around the edges of the pond bob rotting crab apples. The rest of the surface is completely still, save for the occasional ripple cause by pond skaters and a particularly tenacious dragonfly. There's one spot where the algae is separated, is if the water has been recently disturbed by something with force.
As you peer into the depths, you notice a glint of something shining back as the sunlight hits it.
> use cultivator on glint

> use cultivator on glint
You hold the cultivator as far back along the handle as you can manage, and lower the opposite end into the water. Keeping your eyes on the glinting shape, you keep lowering down until you feel the bed of the pond. Slowly, you push forwards along the bottom until you think you're round about where the shining object is, and hook it back towards you.

When you get it out of the water, you can't believe what you're looking at. You rub it on your shirt just to make sure... It's a diamond ring. An expensive one, by the look of it - an engagement ring, maybe, discarded by a spurned lover? An unwanted complication? However it ended up here, and whoever it belonged to, you don't concentrate on as you put it in your shirt pocket.
> n

> n

You find yourself standing on the edge of a sparkling stream, its crystalline water lapping at the grassy banks as it meanders around pebbles and stones. The air here is clear and refreshing, the trees not as thick as deeper within the woods. Part of you wishes you could sit here forever, soaking up the atmosphere and listening to the water. You feel completely at peace. The path south leads deeper into the woods, whilst to the north the trees appear to thin out even further.
You can go south or north.

> n

> n
You emerge from the woods to a calming sight: A great lake, silent and still, stretches almost as far as the eye can see to the east and west. Across on the northern shore, also a large distance away, you can see the village you spotted when leaving the shack. You're a little closer to it now, but it's still too far away to consider walking to, and you doubt you'd have the stamina to swim there. A little way down toward the lake's edge, a wooden jetty struts into the water.
 Tied to the jetty is a length of thick cable, one end of which disappears into the water. Small bubbles occasionally rise to the surface around it.
You take this moment to sit and rest, gathering your thoughts. Where are you? Why are you here, in this place? How did you end up naked and alone, in an old shack in the middle of nowhere? You have so many unanswered questions. You've managed to put off thinking about it too much, just wanting to get out and find answers as you explore your surroundings, trying to find your way back home.

Home.

Where is home? You realise you're not entirely sure, and that scares the hell out of you. You know your name, your gender, your likes and dislikes... But what about family? Friends? Where are you from? How do you know this isn't home?

You close your eyes. No. No, you're sure of it - you don't belong here. You don't understand why, but you know this isn't where you should be. As you open them again, for a moment everything appears fuzzy, like static on an old TV screen covering the landscape. As soon as you focus on it, it's gone. Stress, maybe. With that, you stand up and try to organise your thoughts. You need to find some answers, and you'll stop at nothing to get them.
You can see a cable and some plastic barrels.
You can go south or north.

> pull cable

> pull cable
You wrap your gloved hands around the cable, the rubber grip providing a solid hold as you heave the cable backwards onto the jetty. There's a sudden give, as if something has been dislodged from the bottom of the lake.

You continue to pull, until a wooden crate breaks the surface of the lake, the cable tied around it rightly. With a final heave, you manage to bring the crate up onto the jetty.
> cut cable with loppers

> cut cable with loppers
You untuck the loppers from your belt loop, open them up, and snap them hard around the cable. It takes a few attempts, but you manage to cut through it!
> use pick axe on crate

> use pick axe on crate
You stand with your legs apart to keep your footing, and swing the pick axe as hard as you can into the wooden crate. With a tremendous crash, the crate explodes into splinters, dust and debris.
> x crate

> x crate
Splinters of wood surround what's left of the crate. Many of the planks are still intact, despite your smashing it open.
> use nails on planks

> use nails on planks
You gather the planks together, and overlap each one slightly with the next. Using the mallet you found in the farm house pantry, you hammer the nails in to create a stable wooden platform of planks.
> use blueprints

> use blueprints
You take a look at the blueprints. The barrels for floatation are here, the planks you obtained from the crate are nailed together, the cable is cut free from the jetty and ready to use, and you're carrying the oar you found in the boat shed. That's... That's everything. You don't know why, but you feel like this is the right thing to do - the right way to go. You need to get across that lake. To find answers, to discover why you're here, who put you here, and where you're meant to be.

You drag the barrels out of the lake, hauling them ashore, and drag them on top of the board of planks you've created as a platform. grabbing the cable, you feed it between the barrels in a cross shape and over the planks and back again, before wrapping each end around itself in a thick knot.

With a tremendous effort, you shove hard against your creation, getting it out onto the surface of the water. With one final effort, you push the nearside down below the surface, making the whole thing flip over with a great splash.

It may not be much, but you now have your very own raft!
> n

> n
You are aboard your homemade raft, gently paddling your way across a large lake, roughly midway between a jetty to the south and a shoreline to the north. The water calmly laps against the sides of your raft.
You can go south or north.

> n

> n
Both you and your raft have arrived at the northern shore of the lake intact. Hopefully, you're one step closer to finding the answers you seek. You moor your raft on the edge of the lake. A small shingled beach crunches underfoot as you step upon it, meeting thick forest just a short distance ahead. Looking up and down the shoreline, you don't see anyone at all - this place seems as deserted as everywhere else. There isn't a jetty or anything over on this side of the lake, but one thing stands out: There's a stone statue here, seemingly decorational, looking out over the lake. This strikes you as rather odd, but then the whole journey has been full of questions and light on asnwers.
You can see a statue and a beach.
You can go south.

> x statue

> x statue
The statue is recognisably human, with carved limbs, torso and a head. The proportions are disturbingly realistic, although you're not sure whether it's meant to be male or female. The head has lines carved into the side facing the forest and a smooth oval surface facing the lake, giving the impression its looking out, waiting for someone to arrive. You feel it watching you, as if it's trying to speak to you or get your attention, despite the fact it doesn't have a face.
The statue stands atop a carved block, which has a square pattern cut into it. Underneath the patterrn is what appears to be writing.
> use tiara on statue

> use tiara on statue
You place the tiara atop the statue's head, with the front facing out over the lake.
> use diamond ring on statue

> use diamond ring on statue
You place the diamond ring over one of the fingers statues. It fits perfectly, and holds in place.
> use locket on statue

> use locket on statue
You place the chain around the statue's neck, with the locket hanging facing the lake.
> x block

> x block
You bend down again to check the block the statue is stood upon, when you notice the square carving on the front of it has disappeared. As you go to stand back up again, you see something you can't explain - a disturbance in the air, in front of where the carving was. The more you look at it, the less you can make it out, but you are drawn to it. It feels familiar to you, but you don't know why... This is what the writing was referring to! You force yourself to focus on the mid-distance, slowly moving your hands towards what now appears to be a cube of disturbed air in front of the statue's plinth.

As your fingers reach the area, it forms a shape in your mind - a cube. The air moves around it as if it wasn't there, but you feel it in your hands. You know this cube belongs to you. You know its purpose, and why it's here, and how it will help you get out - You just can't remember.

You take the strange, void cube with you, recalling what the words on the block said: Take it underground, beyond a door, and leave it there. Words you wrote, for yourself
> s

> s
You are aboard your homemade raft, gently paddling your way across a large lake, roughly midway between a jetty to the south and a shoreline to the north. The water calmly laps against the sides of your raft.
You can go south or north.

> s

> s
You emerge from the woods to a calming sight: A great lake, silent and still, stretches almost as far as the eye can see to the east and west. Across on the northern shore, also a large distance away, you can see the village you spotted when leaving the shack. You're a little closer to it now, but it's still too far away to consider walking to, and you doubt you'd have the stamina to swim there. A little way down toward the lake's edge, a wooden jetty struts into the water.

You can see a raft and a crate.
You can go south or north.

> s

> s

You find yourself standing on the edge of a sparkling stream, its crystalline water lapping at the grassy banks as it meanders around pebbles and stones. The air here is clear and refreshing, the trees not as thick as deeper within the woods. The constant yet peaceful sound of the stream makes you thirsty; the water looks good enough to drink. You feel completely at peace. The path south leads deeper into the woods, whilst to the north the trees appear to thin out even further.
You can go south or north.

> s

> s
You are deep in thick woodland, at the western end of a trail. It peters out from here, although you can follow it back to the east which will take you to the entrance of the woods. A small, algae coated pond fills an earthen pit in the ground behind you, a gnarled crab apple tree standing at its edge, reaching skyward to grasp what sunlight filters through.
You can see several pond skaters and a dragonfly.
You can go east or north.

> use torch on hollow

> use torch on hollow
You switch the torch on, taking a moment to wonder at the sense of what you're about to do. It shines a weak light into the hollow under the tree.
> in

> in
You take another look at the note you found in the jacket pocket of the scarecrow. This... is the place. You're sure of it. The crudely drawn map points to this woodland; this tree. Maybe it points to this hollow...
Guided by the torch you're carrying, you get down onto the ground, and crawl into the hollow...
You are crouched just inside the hollow of the tree. From what little room you have to manoeuvre in here, you can look up to see the solid trunk of the not far above your head - the hollow doesn't extend up inside. Shining your torch further infront of you illuminates a tunnel stretching beneath the earth, heading in westerly direction. The tunnel gets narrower as it dsecends further underground. From here, you can also go back out into the open.
You can go out or west.

> w

> w
You are crawling on hands and knees in the entrance to a narrow tunnel which leads underground from the hollow in the tree. A little daylight filters through from the east, whilst the tunnel narrows even more as it curves southward. You stop, just for a moment, to question the sanity of what you're doing. You awoke in a shack in the middle of the countryside, have explored farms, woods and fields, and now you're crawling on your knees through a tunnel dug into the earth. How the hell does this help? There have to be answers somewhere.
You can go east or south.

> s

> s
You are crawling on your belly through the soil of a very tight underground tunnel, with barely enough room to move backwards or forwards. The earth encompasses you on all sides, your shoulders brushing the dirt around you as you move along. You can, if you try, shuffle northwards along the tunnel to a point where you can crawl. You can also shuffle downhill to the southwest, holding the torch in your mouth as you move through the claustrophobic space. There is very little air and very little light, even from the torch.
You can go north or southwest.

> sw

> sw
You are pulling yourself along an underground tunnel, laying completely prone as you do so. The tunnel descends to the west going deeper underground, whilst to the northeast it curves uphill. You can just about struggle in either direction. You close your eyes and try not to panic as you wave away thoughts of becoming stuck, the battieries in the torch dying, running out of air...
You can go northeast or west.

> w

> w
You can see space ahead! The mouth of the tunnel widens slightly, before opening up somewhat. You wriggle to the end of the tunnel and drop out onto the floor a foot or so below you. Somewhat relieved, you get to your feet.

You are standing in a roughly hewn underground chamber, surrounded by compact soil. There's barely an inch of space above your head, and you can't stretch your arms further out than your elbows. Remarkably you can still breathe, as musty and still the air is this far down.

In front of you is something unexpected a door. A steel door.

Your mind boggles as you try to make sense of what you're experiencing. You're underground, deep underground, in a tiny chamber surrounded by dirt. You've crawled through an opening in the base of a tree, hidden by a pond in the middle of thick woodland, to get here and you don't know why, except your desire to find out where you are, how you got here, and why you found yourself here. And now, having decided of your own free will to reach this unlikely point, you're standing facing a steel door underground, seemingly with no other access to this spot.

It can't be coincidence you ended up here, nor can this tunnel and the door have been placed here without purpose. You're anxious to see what lies beyond; where this strange adventure will take you next.

You can, if you wish, climb back into the tunnel be heading east. The door lies to the south.

You can go east or south.

> x steel door

> x steel door
The light of your torch relects off the slab of steel in front of you, set into the compact earth which surrounds it. Running across the base of the door is a long horizontal bar about eight inches from the ground.
> use jack on horizontal bar

> use jack on horizontal bar
You wind the jack until it's fully closed, and wedge it beneath the steel bar running across the base of the door. It takes some pushing into the compact earth, but you manage to make it fit.

Again you wind the handle on the jack, this time in the opposite direction. There's a shower of earth from above you, but the door begins to open! With as much effort as you can muster, you continue to wind until the jack is fully extended, giving you enough space to duck beneath the door and head further underground.
> s

> s
On the other side of the door isn't what you expect, even taking into account how you got here. The note, the tree, the crawl through the earth...

You are walking through a tunnel deep underground. The whole thing appears to be made from glass, although no joints or supporting material is evident. The tunnel is roughly octagonal, each surface identical. It also appears to self illuminate, although you don't understand how, but you can see all the way along it; it stretches far to the south. In the other direction, the tunnel ends at a darkened portal - the door, leading back into the earth.

The surfaces of the tunnel are completely clear, you're sure of it, but you can't see anything beyond the glass. You get a sense of space out there, that you're looking at something, you just can't see it. There is no earth, no rock, no anything. It's just blackness. The glass doesn't reflect anything back at you either.
You can go north or south.

> s

> s
You are walking along a glass tunnel. To the south, the tunnel ends at what you might call a door. You can sense it's a different space, the end of the tunnel and the start of something else, but you can't really rationalise it in any logical way. Much futher away, to the north, the glass tunnel becoms a darkened patch of space, leading back the way you originally came.
You can go north or south.

> s

> s
You are in The White Room.
You can go north.

> drop cube

> drop cube

Thank you for playing The Shack! I hope you enjoyed the experience.

Don't worry: You'll be back in the protagonist's shoes in future adventures!

I'd like to thank the team at textadventures.co.uk for keeping the genre alive and creating Quest, the tool this was written with. I'd also like to thank the various contributors at freesounds.org for taking the time to record the atmospheric sounds used in this game, Mark Ferrari and all the other artists who make their work available for others to use, and finally everyone who playtested The Shack, including Rebecca, my significantly better half.

